      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The French Revolution was a complex and multifaceted movement that began with the storming of the Bastille on July 14, 1789, as a culmination of the monarchy's financial struggles and the people's growing discontent with the absolute rule of King Louis XVI. As economic hardship and food shortages worsened, the National Assembly, representing the Third Estate, adopted the Tennis Court Oath, vowing to continue their work on a new constitution despite the king's orders to disband. The following years saw the rise of influential figures like Maximilien Robespierre, who would lead the Committee of Public Safety during the Reign of Terror, a period of extreme violence and repression from 1793 to 1794. Meanwhile, the queen, Marie Antoinette, became a symbol of the monarchy's extravagance and was eventually tried and executed in 1793. Napoleon Bonaparte, a brilliant and ambitious military leader, eventually seized power in 1799, marking the end of the Revolution and beginning a new era of French history.",
      "source": "target",
